1220":"about 1220","Abt 1190":"about 1190","Malpas, Cheshire West and Chester, England":"Malpas, Cheshire, England","Malpas, Cheshire, England":"Malpas, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Malpas","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Malpass  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Malpass","meanings":["English (Staffordshire and Gloucestershire): habitational name, chiefly from either of two places called Malpas (Cheshire, England and Monmouthshire, Wales); perhaps also occasionally from other minor places so called in England (e.g. in Berkshire, Cornwall, and Yorkshire) or from various places called Malpas or Maupas in France. The placenames derive from Old French <i>mal</i> ‘bad’ + <i>pas</i> ‘passage’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Malpas was born about 1190, in Malpas, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Dan David le Clerk, was 21 and his mother, Catherine Vaughan, was 22. He had at least 1 son with Marjorie de Lynton. He died about 1252, in his hometown, at the age of 64."},"et":{"Abt 1190–Abt 1252":"umbes 1190–umbes 1252","1190–1252":"1190–1252","1197–1272":"1197–1272","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1205–Female":"1205–Surnud","1182–1245":"1182–1245","1190–Female":"1190–Surnud","1210–1255":"1210–1255","1225–1279":"1225–1279","1170–1217":"1170–1217","1170–1220":"1170–1220","1190":"1190","about 1190":"umbes 1190","1220":"1220","1197":"1197","1252":"1252","1272":"1272","1182":"1182","1170":"1170","Abt 1252":"umbes 1252","1217":"1217","1205":"1205","1225":"1225","about 1217":"umbes 1217","1279":"1279","1245":"1245","Abt 1210":"umbes 1210","1255":"1255","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","about 1220":"umbes 1220","Abt 1190":"umbes 1190","Malpas, Cheshire West and Chester, England":"Malpas, Cheshire, England","Malpas, Cheshire, England":"Malpas, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1190–Abt 1252":"noin 1190–noin 1252","1190–1252":"1190–1252","1197–1272":"1197–1272","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1205–Female":"1205–Kuollut","1182–1245":"1182–1245","1190–Female":"1190–Kuollut","1210–1255":"1210–1255","1225–1279":"1225–1279","1170–1217":"1170–1217","1170–1220":"1170–1220","1190":"1190","about 1190":"noin 1190","1220":"1220","1197":"1197","1252":"1252","1272":"1272","1182":"1182","1170":"1170","Abt 1252":"noin 1252","1217":"1217","1205":"1205","1225":"1225","about 1217":"noin 1217","1279":"1279","1245":"1245","Abt 1210":"noin 1210","1255":"1255","1200":"120